TY  - JOUR
T1  - Modeling Organizational Species' Interdependence in an Ecological Community: An Input-Output Approach
AU  - Beard, Donald W.
AU  - Dess, Gregory G.
Y1  - 1988/07/01
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1988.4306941
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1988.4306941
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 362
EP  - 373
VL  - 13
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - An organizational species' resource inputs and outputs comprise its most fundamental openness to its environment. An input-output model based on each species' resource exchanges with other species is a useful framework by which to operationalize and model the community-ecology perspective in organization theory. An input-output model provides a means of identifying each organizational species' niche within a given ecology and a means of modeling each species' direct and indirect dependence on other species for resources.
AB  - An organizational species' resource inputs and outputs comprise its most fundamental openness to its environment. An input-output model based on each species' resource exchanges with other species is a useful framework by which to operationalize and model the community-ecology perspective in organization theory. An input-output model provides a means of identifying each organizational species' niche within a given ecology and a means of modeling each species' direct and indirect dependence on other species for resources.
