TY  - JOUR
T1  - Implementing Entrepreneurial Ideas: The Case for Intention
AU  - Bird, Barbara
Y1  - 1988/07/01
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1988.4306970
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1988.4306970
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 442
EP  - 453
VL  - 13
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Entrepreneurial intentions, entrepreneurs' states of mind that direct attention, experience, and action toward a business concept, set the form and direction of organizations at their inception. Subsequent organizational outcomes such as survival, development (including written plans), growth, and change are based on these intentions. The study of entrepreneurial intentions provides a way of advancing entrepreneurship research beyond descriptive studies and helps to distinguish entrepreneurial activity from strategic management.
AB  - Entrepreneurial intentions, entrepreneurs' states of mind that direct attention, experience, and action toward a business concept, set the form and direction of organizations at their inception. Subsequent organizational outcomes such as survival, development (including written plans), growth, and change are based on these intentions. The study of entrepreneurial intentions provides a way of advancing entrepreneurship research beyond descriptive studies and helps to distinguish entrepreneurial activity from strategic management.
